  "description": "A continuous map is a function between topological spaces that preserves the structure of nearness — it does not tear, break, or introduce sudden jumps. If two points are close in the source, their images are close in the target. Continuous maps are the structure-preserving functions of topology, just as linear maps are the structure-preserving functions of linear algebra and group homomorphisms are the structure-preserving functions of group theory.\nThe oldest formulation of continuity is the epsilon-delta definition from calculus. Given metric spaces (X,dX)(X, d_X) and (Y,dY)(Y, d_Y), a function f:X→Yf: X \\to Y is continuous at a point xx if for every ε\u0026gt;0\\varepsilon \u0026gt; 0 there exists δ\u0026gt;0\\delta \u0026gt; 0 such that whenever dX(x,x′)\u0026lt;δd_X(x, x\u0026#x27;) \u0026lt; \\delta, we have dY(f(x),f(x′))\u0026lt;εd_Y(f(x), f(x\u0026#x27;)) \u0026lt; \\varepsilon. In plain language: you can make ff\u0026rsquo;s output as close as you like to f(x)f(x) by keeping the input close enough to xx. Augustin-Louis Cauchy gave the first rigorous statement of this idea in Cours d\u0026rsquo;analyse (1821), and Karl Weierstrass sharpened it to the modern epsilon-delta form in his Berlin lectures of the 1860s.\n",
